Question: Q8
Value: Thanks for setting this up! I really have mixed feelings about this topic. Clearly, many of us (including myself) are extremely aware of climate change and pollution, but I am not convinced that cutting down the number of conferences is really a good starting point if I look at the cost/benefit tradeoff. I think the best way would be to live stream (including the possibility of asking questions) the event but still have it also happening in a physical location.   * Starting with the pros: I think it would be extremely profitable for the entire community to be able to attend every conference *online* and for *free*. In this way, more people could be exposed to new research even when there is not enough budget/time to fully attend it.  * The main reason to go to a conference is networking. And this cannot be substituted by online media.  * It is difficult to fully attend an online conference: eg. we would not set up an out-of-office autoreply. This means that we try to squeeze the conference into an already busy schedule.   * Traveling by train should be encouraged but not forced. Sometimes, traveling 500km by train can take many hours (and often this time is private time, given that it happens during the weekend) and multiple changes. Moreover, at least in Europe, trains are often way more expensive than planes (and this affects the always shrinking budget for academia).   * Working in Academia is clearly not a stable/highly paid job. We do it because we like it. I find the possibility of traveling to cool places as one of the rare benefits that we as researchers get.

Question: Q8
Value: Travel and the related tourism dollars it generates are vital for certain parts of the country and world. In addition, encouraging people to see locations and interact with people they would otherwise would not, and may maintain stereotyped or media-driven beliefs about is healthy for social/human development. The goals of this inquiry are excellent however, there are other ways to achieve this goal without harming the benefits to individuals as well as the income we provide service industry workers who are already frequently losing their jobs to technological advances. Lobbying for cleaner and more accessible travel options, supporting airlines or bus companies that also support the environment as well as companies that utilize new models of transportation, etc. will support the environment and keep people interacting with one another in meaningful ways that Zoom Meetings and online photo galleries have yet to achieve. Also, remember your students who need to save money when traveling but also need to practice presenting and networking under a variety of conditions. At a time when many professional organizations are looking to engage the public and take a more intentional and active role in society, virtual meetings can be a tool but cannot replicate human-to-human interaction. It is not that I dislike technology, for instance, I think poster sessions should be made virtual, either through a smartboard or like device to reduce the cost and hassle of poster printing and presenters should have the option of submitting proposals to be presented virtually, but that this virtual option should not take away or reduce the benefits of national conferences. Finally, smatterings of regional conferences seem more wasteful and less inviting or effective for developing scholars hoping to meet or hear the work of a scholar not in their region and who is not going to attend multiple regional conferences. To that point, I urge you to remember first-generation students, who absolutely need lowered costs but also environments that nurture network building as one's network often has a great weight on the quality of one's work and career.

Value: I am quite isolated because I'm sort of the only linguist in a languages department.  (My colleagues aren't linguists; we rarely have guest speakers unless I invite them myself; etc.) So conferences are CRUCIAL for me to network with linguists.  The socializing is much more important than the intellectual content.  So any new policy should account for people for whom conferences are their main lifeline to the socio-intellectual environment of the field.  I think a few conferences could go well online, especially ones where people pre-read a paper and then talk about it or something, or the apparent success of CUNY this year.  But I also personally really enjoy going to conferences and I hope to continue doing so in the future. Question: Q8
Value: I love that I get to travel for conferences. I don't feel like it's wasted. I often take a personal vacation as part of the trip, and/or visit libraries where I can't get references via inter-library loan. I'm an early career researcher (currently completing my PhD), so I already notice I'm less excited about re-visiting some of the same locations (for example, Venice), I've also often caught some kind of illness on flights, and the expenses make it challenging. I have mixed feelings about conferences. In many ways, they're great, and I really don't like the suggestions of effectively punishing researchers or even punishing research for participating in international conferences. At the same time, I feel like it should be more efficient. One example is that some conference strictly limit the number of presentations from one submitter, and we could be more efficient by allowing two or more. (Yes, that causes other schedule and resource issues, I understand. But it would be more efficient for travel impact!) At the same time, I love it when conferences put talks online (and asynchronous is important: I missed a zoom talk this week that was scheduled for 6am my time (elsewhere in the world) because it was a busy week and I couldn't get myself out of bed that early). But it's not so good to participate in a conference remotely. Actually the best online conference I've participated in (of very few, I admit) was probably the Polish Cognitive Linguistics Association annual online conference, which was remarkably simple: just a Google site, and everything through uploaded PDFs and text-chat on the website, no video or audio at all. And it's not highly prestigious, and wasn't the "best" conference, but it was a wonderful way to add another conference to my schedule without any travel expenses and I'd like to see more of that. But not being somewhere in person means not talking to people in the hallways and during the breaks, which is one of the biggest benefits. For the annual grad student conference at my university several years ago it was normal to synchronously broadcast the event online, which was extremely convenient-- I could watch talks without leaving the house-- but I did notice the downside which was that it ended up in me not being there to sit in the audience and make the presenters feel welcomed, so I think attendance went up after (for other, technical/budgetary reasons) the online video feature was abandoned. In the end, honestly, I don't feel that this survey did a very good job of presenting any solid alternatives to in-person conferences, but I would be very open to exploring some. How do we replace the in-person contact? Just as a random idea, today I was trying and failing to contact a researcher by email because all I could find were old email addresses from last decade, and I have no idea if they got my message, so this makes me think that conference organizers should do a better job of gathering contact lists and, assuming everyone would consent, publishing them on the conference website, so we could talk with each other, without having to FIND people in person (which can be hard anyway if we don't know what they look like). There are many considerations, but I think they need to be made in a bigger context, not just trying to offset carbon first and hoping it doesn't have a negative impact on researchers and research, because it would. We should reduce carbon. But we shouldn't do it blindly without some good ideas about what to do instead. And honestly, I have really mixed feelings when academics, who generally lead the world in progressive policies anyway, take it upon themselves to sacrifice for the planet when the majority of the population, including major corporations, commuters, etc., are all really much more responsible than we are, and when our travel is genuinely good for the world. I believe in science, so I believe in sharing it. Think about the irony of canceling a conference about reducing carbon emissions. Or the tragedy of doing anything that would get in the way of fieldwork for documenting languages that will die out soon due to climate change.
